We Neapolitans love him and are profoundly proud of him

After WW2 and until the 70s the Bourbon Tunnel was used as storage for impounded vehicles.
Originally however the underground tunnel, commissioned in 1853 by King Ferdinando II of Bourbon, was intended to be used by the royal family as a strategic escape route in case of emergency.
.

The Peace Pagoda in Battersea Park (London) was a special gift to Londoners by Nichidatsu Fuji, founder of the Japanese Buddhist movement.
After the tragedy of the atomic bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, Nichidatsu built pagodas around the world as shrines to peace. This one was completed in 1985, the same year Nichidatsu died at the age of 100. .
.

Within its 16th century walls, the Old City of Jerusalem is divided into four uneven quarters: Muslim, Christian, Armenian and Jewish. 
Wherever you look you will see "Jerusalem stone", a type of white limestone so dear to Jerusalem that Municipal laws require that all buildings be faced with local Jerusalem stone

The lowest point on earth, at 423 m below sea level, is home to the Dead Sea. Although it really is a lake, its 33% salinity makes it 10 times more salty than the average sea water. Whilst this makes it impossible for anything to live in it, it helps you float almost as if you could "sit" on the surface of the water - as elegantly demonstrated by me in the picture above

The Keshet Cave is a natural limestone arch. Yep, an arch, not a cave. So what's with the name? Keshet means rainbow in Hebrew and the cave did actual exist long ago, until it collapsed, leaving just part of the arched limestone ceiling intact, with a drop of 50m

View from the top of the Baha'i gardens in Haifa, overlooking the tomb of the first Baha'i prophet. The Baha'i are a monotheistic religious group which loosely speaking believe that all other monotheistic religions are equally correct. The One God that all believe in, sent to the people prophets who carried a version of God's teachings that were appropriate for the time the people lived in.

My mum gav me a prayer scroll to fit in the Kotel wall. The Kotel is the closest Jews are allowed to pray to the foundation stone, the holiest place for a Jew, which lies behind the wall. The wall is also known as Wailing Wall, maybe due to the fact that some Jews come to it to weep over the destruction of the holy temples that lied behind it, or maybe due to the way some Jews rock their upper body during prayer giving from the distance an appearance of desperation
